  "prompt": "What is the legal history of money laundering prohibitions?",
  "response": "Here's an overview of the legal history of money laundering prohibitions:\n\n1. Early Origins\n- Informal money laundering practices existed for centuries\n- Criminals sought to disguise illegal income's origins\n\n2. Initial Formal Anti-Money Laundering (AML) Legislation\n- United States Bank Secrecy Act (1970)\n- First comprehensive legal framework targeting financial crimes\n- Required banks to report large cash transactions\n- Established reporting and record-keeping requirements\n\n3. International Development\n- 1980s: Growing international recognition of money laundering as a significant financial crime\n- 1989: Financial Action Task Force (FATF) established\n- Developed global standards for combating money laundering\n\n4. Major Legislative Milestones\n- U.S. Money Laundering Control Act (1986)\n- Criminalized money laundering as a separate federal crime\n- Expanded legal tools for prosecuting financial crimes\n\n5. Post-9/11 Developments\n- USA PATRIOT Act (2001)\n- Strengthened AML regulations\n- Enhanced international information sharing\n- Increased focus on terrorism financing\n\n6. Ongoing Global Regulation\n- Continuous evolution of international AML standards\n- Increased technological monitoring\n- Expanding regulatory frameworks across jurisdictions\n\nThe legal landscape continues to adapt to emerging financial technologies and criminal strategies.",
